description.plain:
‘Kingston,’ the first new song since her 2017’s sophomore self-titled LP, is quintessential Faye Webster. Awash in the haze of a humid Georgia summer, all lovestruck and dewy, ‘Kingston’ glimmers with a hushed glitz: a mellowed punctuation of brass, the twang of pedal-steel, feather-light vocals unfurling like a sigh, and slinking hues of R&B.

-Faye Webster on her Spotify “About” page

Sometimes it’s done to discover your subconscious emotions, or simply to remember them. This line is just Faye’s way of saying she’s in love and every moment with them is ‘a dream’.

annotations:
I wonder if you got home
 But we just said goodbye
It’s implying how the narrator and their partner just said goodbye but the narrator already wants to text/call to ask if they got home safe. Showing how much they care about their partner

You said you can’t change your haircut
 But it looks good anyway
 I kinda wonder where you got it
 And I doubt you even paid

Faye is implying a beautiful expression of her love for this partner, despite all their flaws and insecurities. She does this by explaining how she likes their haircut even if they might not be too impressed with it themselves. She sings that she doubt they “even paid” likely because this partner cut their hair on their own, explaining why it might not be such a flattering look. Faye says she kinda wonders where they got it because she is interested in a haircut done by this partner since she feels it would be a romantic experience, even if the haircut itself might not look too good, finding beauty in all their flaws.

You looked back at me once
 But I looked back two times

This line implies that the speakers attraction for the love interest is far greater than the lover. The act of looking back when leaving a date or a meeting is often done for many reasons. In this case, it symbolises the speakers fondness towards the moment and person, as the moment the outing has ended she will return to missing them.

annotations:
I know you’ve been having nightmares lately
 And I’m sorry I fall asleep first
Faye regrets that she can’t give her partner the same comfort and happiness that they give her, even in this mundane vignette of them sleeping in the same bed.

You weigh just as much as me, don’t you (ah)
 I can feel it when we touch

Reminiscent of the metaphor of “walking on air” when you’re in love with somebody or feeling “weightless.” Faye and her romantic interest both weighing the same means that the attraction between them is mutual.

I didn’t know that you were right in front of me
 Until I looked out
Perhaps this person has been in Faye’s life for a good amount of time. It’s only now that they’ve grown closer and Faye has found this hidden source of happiness, connection, and fulfillment.

I didn’t know that I was capable of being happy right now
 But you showed me how
Sets up the theme of the song. Faye’s partner isn’t making her cry in a bad way – in fact, it’s the opposite. They’re helping her be happy in a time when she didn’t think that was possible.

You make me wanna cry in a good way
 You make me wanna cry in a good way
 You make me wanna cry in a good way
 You make me wanna cry in a good way

A very common feeling in relationships is an overwhelming feeling of joy and euphoria towards the other person. One way to let out emotions is crying, whether in a good or bad way, and faye can only express these emotions through tears of joy around this person

annotations: That silence is actually hurt

She realises that someone’s lack of words can hurt just as much as no words at all, and the way in which she sings it and prolongs the word “hurt” not only feeds into the chorus but is sung as if she is on the brink of tears and adds conveying how hurt she feels.

I just don’t care if it hurts
 ’Cause it hurts me too

Webster is able to finally speak up and reveal true thoughts and emotions, but this person is hurt by her songs. Even if Faye is merely expressing herself. The person at hand plays victim, but Faye insists that through attempting to heal through songwriting she and the person, are both losing nothing.

The nonchalant tone continues here as she realizes that regardless of what she does, one of the two parties is going to get inevitably hurt. If Faye doesn’t write lyrics, she is hurt and unable to process the pain. If Faye does, she remains hurt by the rejection and her lover is hurt by what she is saying. This leads to her no longer caring for the outcome and just needing to get it off her chest through her lyrics.

And I am done changing words
 Just so my songs sound prettier

Webster’s apathetic nature hints that she simply, feels that the best way she can articulate herself is through the straightforward lyrics that show her thoughts as they are, without sugarcoating.

She is also ignoring her mum’s wishes and feels that although happier songs may be prettier. Her pain as a result of the unrequited love prevents her from being able to write uplifting songs as she recovers.

The day that I said I loved you
 You didn’t say it in return
When Faye feels ready to confess her love to her partner, she is stumped by the fact that she is a victim of one sided love.

But loving you has only
 Made me cry twice or so

Faye is talking to her lover and is telling them that though her songs are mostly sad and stem from pain and hardship. Her lover rarely hurts her, seen in that she has only cried a handful of times throughout the span of their relationship.

Though she may be minimizing the negative impact of this person on her life, the use of “and so” means the number of times this person has made her cry is not exactly two, and possibly more than she is letting the person know.

My mother told me one day
 She’s tired of my sad songs

Faye’s mother is voicing her opinion to her daughter, out of concern, about the many sad songs with dark themes that are being written. The sad songs seem to be the only ones that naturally come to Faye considering her current circumstances which hinder her from writing songs with brighter themes.

And what am I ’posed to do when
 My dad cries in front of me?

Faye is clueless on what to do when her dad is seemingly deeply affected by her sentimental songs on this individual, so much so that he allows himself to cry in front of his daughter.

Seeing her dad cry allowed her to understand the palpable impact of this individual on her life, so much so that her songs written about this person are able to bring tears to people’s eyes.

Do I just close my eyes and
 Pretend like I didn’t see?

Faye is pondering if turning a blind eye to how truly sad her songs are, will help her with healing. But from her tone, which is somewhat disdainful, as she thinks it may be difficult for her to heal when continuing to write in such a negative and pessimistic lens.

I just don’t care if it hurts
 ’Cause it hurts me too

Webster is able to finally speak up and reveal true thoughts and emotions, but this person is hurt by her songs. Even if Faye is merely expressing herself. The person at hand plays victim, but Faye insists that through attempting to heal through songwriting she and the person, are both losing nothing.

The nonchalant tone continues here as she realizes that regardless of what she does, one of the two parties is going to get inevitably hurt. If Faye doesn’t write lyrics, she is hurt and unable to process the pain. If Faye does, she remains hurt by the rejection and her lover is hurt by what she is saying. This leads to her no longer caring for the outcome and just needing to get it off her chest through her lyrics.

And I am done changing words
 Just so my songs sound prettier

Webster’s apathetic nature hints that she simply, feels that the best way she can articulate herself is through the straightforward lyrics that show her thoughts as they are, without sugarcoating.

She is also ignoring her mum’s wishes and feels that although happier songs may be prettier. Her pain as a result of the unrequited love prevents her from being able to write uplifting songs as she recovers.

body.plain: The fifth song on Faye Webster’s third full-length album, “Jonny”  finds Faye wondering about what she wants or looks for in love and life, and finds herself – against her own best interests – finding her thoughts drifting back towards an old lover, foreshadowing the ending of the album with “Jonny (Reprise)”.

annotations: Not that I’ve paid attention
this could be a refusal to admit she notices what he does, even if it is a minor detail. this also shows how one-sided their relationship was
Sometimes I’ll pray but I will never close my eyes

Closing your eyes during prayer isn’t seen as necessary but many do it to avoid visual stimuli or distractions. Some believe closing your eyes allows a gateway to God as your turn away from Earth. It is mainly seen as subliminal and a way to act out of your own body. She may be indicating that she doesn’t believe in religion. Praying could be false hope or escapism for her as she doesn’t believe in it but does it anyways in the hope of finding meaning in life.

This wasn’t ’posed to be a love song
 But I guess it is now, isn’t it?

Faye did not intend for this song to be about Jonny, as she reflects on her feelings of loneliness and hopelessness (first two verses). However, as Faye confronts how she is currently feeling, she begins to reminisce on Jonny in a desperate manner, and almost even blames him for her current emotional state (chorus)

And get over how my dog is my best friend
 And he doesn’t even know what my name is
Webster implies through this line that she is emotionally attached to something that cannot reciprocate her love, comparing her dog to Jonny.
But you haven’t said it out loud

The distance in the relationship bewteen Jonny and Faye Webster is exemplified when she notes that Jonny may never hear the song, possibly because they never talk about the issues in their relationship

Jonny, did you ever love me?
 Jonny, help me figure it out
as she is finding herself, she looks back and dwells on her old relationship with ‘jonny’ and questions the so called love he had for her
Why the hell did I paint these walls white?
White or light-colored walls make a room appear more spacious or empty. Faye uses this imagery to portray how her life seems more empty or lonely.
